<HEADLINE>
<P>
YEMENI LEADER BACKS TRIBALISM, ISLAM, ARMS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yemen's top tribal chief says tribalism and Islam should retain their 
importance in a multi-party political system and that tribesmen should have the 
traditional right to carry weapons. 
</P>
<P>
"In my opinion, pluralism is better than a one-party system, but it should be 
based on the Yemeni people's beliefs, which are mainly Islam," Sheik Abdullah 
ibn Hussein Ahmar, was quoted Monday as saying in the Emirates newspaper Al 
Ittihad. 
</P>
<P>
Tribesmen will continue to carry weapons because "we consider them part of our 
tradition," he said. 
</P>
<P>
Yemen and South Yemen last November agreed to a political merger and reforms 
including the right to form political parties when the two states finally 
unite. 
</P>
</TEXT>
