<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: FOUNTAIN VALLEY; 
</P>
<P>
POLICE TARGET DRIVERS ON BROOKHURST ST. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Drivers on Brookhurst Street beware! 
</P>
<P>
Police today will begin a monthlong crackdown of even the most minor traffic 
violations on a three-mile section of the street between Adams and Warner 
avenues. 
</P>
<P>
The program, called CASE, Critical Accident Suppression and Enforcement, is 
targeting a stretch of road where the number of collisions has increased 
sharply. 
</P>
<P>
"The focus of this effort is not to issue citations, though many times that 
will be the result of being stopped. . . . The purpose is to reduce the 
accident rate and remove unsafe drivers from the roadway," Police Sgt. Keith R. 
Levin said. 
</P>
<P>
Violations, such as right of way, speed, and following too closely will be 
targeted heavily, Levin said. 
</P>
<P>
Signs reading "Traffic Enforcement Ahead" will be posted along the street to 
warn drivers that officers are working in the area. 
</P>
<P>
Fountain Valley police, who will be working with Huntington Beach police, plan 
to move to a different roadway at the end of the month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
