<HEADLINE>
<P>
BOYS' ATHLETE OF THE WEEK: PEREZ'S DUAL ROLE MAKES HIM THE TALK OF THE MOUND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARTIN BECK, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SANTA ANA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Like many pitchers, Harvey Perez of Saddleback High School talks to himself on 
the baseball mound. But because Perez is also a catcher, few bring such a rare 
perspective to the conversation. 
</P>
<P>
"If I think I'm getting out of control, I'll circle the mound and get down on 
one knee and talk to myself," Perez said. 
</P>
<P>
Perez, The Times' Athlete of the Week, didn't have to say much Wednesday, when 
he held Newport Harbor hitless until allowing a single in the seventh inning. 
</P>
<P>
He also had two hits and four runs batted in the 7-1 Sea View League victory. 
</P>
<P>
Friday, Perez the catcher threw out two runners attempting to steal second base 
in a 5-3 loss to Tustin. 
</P>
<P>
This dual role is a new one for Perez, who played shortstop for Saddleback most 
of last season. He pitched in only one game and played a couple of games at 
catcher at the end of the season. 
</P>
<P>
But this season, Perez, the senior captain who is batting .452, has been 
required to do more, and has showed some improvement. 
</P>
<P>
"He's got a ways to go because he's still trying to learn the (catching) 
position and it's a hard position to learn," said Saddleback Coach Bob Mangram 
said. "But he works hard at it." 
</P>
<P>
Before the one-hitter last week, Perez hadn't been satisfied with the way he 
has handled himself on the mound, despite an 0.88 earned-run average. "I was 
just catching so much that I really wasn't thinking about pitching," he said. 
</P>
<P>
TOP PERFORMERS 
</P>
<P>
Mark Gonzales of La Habra won the 3,200 meters (9:32.68) and the 800 (1:59.30) 
and was named the athlete of the meet at the Valencia Invitational Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
Greg Pearce pitched a four-hit shutout as El Toro defeated Mission Viejo, 2-0, 
Monday and pitched two scoreless innings and earned a save Friday in a 4-1 
victory over Capistrano Valley. 
</P>
<P>
Mark Parlin won the shotput (56-10 3/4) and the discus (161-5) as Esperanza 
defeated El Dorado, 101-29, in an Empire League track and field meet Thursday. 
Friday, he won the discus (171-5 1/2) at the Tustin Relays and Saturday he put 
the shot 53-9 to win the event at the Bishop Amat Invitational. 
</P>
<P>
Karl Van Reusen and Steve Snyder of Edison each had 17 kills as the Chargers 
defeated then-No. 1-ranked Huntington Beach in a Sunset League volleyball 
match. 
</P>
<P>
Harvey Perez 
</P>
<P>
Saddleback High School 
</P>
<P>
* Position: Pitcher/catcher 
</P>
<P>
* Height, Weight, Class: 5-11, 170, Senior 
</P>
<P>
* Last Week: Perez pitched a one-hitter and had four RBIs in a victory over 
Newport Harbor Wednesday. Friday, he threw out two runners trying to steal 
second. 
</P>
<P>
* Season: Perez has an 0.88 earned-run average and is batting .452. 
</P>
</TEXT>
