<P>
NAZI SUSPECT TO BE SENT TO BONN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BONN 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Suspected Nazi war criminal Joseph Schwammberger, wanted for killing and 
deporting thousands of Jews during World War II, will be extradited from 
Argentina next month, the Justice Ministry said today. 
</P>
<P>
The agreement between Bonn and Buenos Aires to bring back the 78-year-old 
Schwammberger to face trial climaxes 17 years of delicate diplomatic 
negotiations since the two countries do not have an extradition agreement. 
</P>
<P>
"The Schwammberger case shows that no one under suspicion of Nazi crimes can be 
certain of escaping justice . . . wherever in the world he may hide," said West 
German Justice Minister Hans Engelhard in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
Schwammberger, arrested by Argentine police in 1987, will be handed over to 
West German officials May 2. He is accused of killing up to 1,000 people -- 
some of them personally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
